attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "bfo:Entity" ("entity") that has temporal parts and that happens, unfolds or develops through time. Sometimes also called perdurants.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the life of an organism, a surgical operation as processual context for a nosocomical infection, the spatiotemporal context occupied by a process of cellular meiosis, the most interesting part of Van Gogh's life, the spatiotemporal region occupied by the development of a cancer tumor

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: An "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") that is part of time.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the time it takes to run a marathon, the duration of a surgical procedure, the moment of death

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: An instance of "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") is a part of time. All parts of time are "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") entities and only "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") entities are parts of time. Time is the entire extent of the temporal universe, a designated individual, which is thus a temporal region itself.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: All instances of "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") are temporal entities, that is, they enter in the relation of (temporal) location with "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") entities. As a particular case, the exact spatiotemporal location of a "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") is this region itself. "snap:Continuant" ("continuant") entities are not temporal entities in the technical sense just explained; they are related to time in a different way, not through temporal location but through a relation of existence at a time or during a period of time (see "snap:Continuant" ("continuant")).

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: Time and "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") entities are entities in their own rights which exist independently of any entities which can be located at them. This view of time can be called "absolutist" or "the container view" in analogy to what is traditionally the case with space (see "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region")).

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") every point of which is not mediately or immediately connected with every other point of which.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the time occupied by the individual games of the World Cup, the time occupied by the individual liaisons in a romantic affair

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") every point of which is mediately or immediately connected with every other point of which.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the 1970s years, the time from the beginning to the end of a heart attack, the time taken up by cellular meiosis

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:ConnectedTemporalRegion" ("connected_temporal_region") lasting for more than a single moment of time.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: any continuous temporal duration during which a process occurs

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:ConnectedTemporalRegion" ("connected_temporal_region") comprising a single moment of time.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: right now, the moment at which a finger is detached in an industrial accident, the moment at which a child is born, the moment of death

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") at or in which "span:ProcessualEntity" ("processual_entity") entities can be located.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the spatiotemporal region occupied by a human life, the spatiotemporal region occupied by the development of a cancer tumor, the spatiotemporal context occupied by a process of cellular meiosis

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: An instance of the "span:SpatiotemporalRegion" ("spatiotemporal_region") is a part of spacetime. All parts of spacetime are "span:SpatiotemporalRegion" ("spatiotemporal_region") entities and only "span:SpatiotemporalRegion" ("spatiotemporal_region") entities are parts of spacetime. In particular, neither "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") entities nor "span:TemporalRegion" ("temporal_region") entities are in BFO parts of spacetime. Spacetime is the entire extent of the spatiotemporal universe, a designated individual, which is thus itself a "span:SpatiotemporalRegion" ("spatiotemporal_region"). Spacetime is among occurrents the analogous of space among "snap:Continuant" ("continuant") entities.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: All instances of "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") are spatiotemporal entities, that is, they enter in the relation of (spatiotemporal) location with "span:SpatiotemporalRegion" ("spatiotemporal_region") entities. As a particular case, the exact spatiotemporal location of a "span:SpatiotemporalRegion" ("spatiotemporal_region") is this region itself.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: Spacetime and "span:SpatiotemporalRegion" ("spatiotemporal_region") entities are entities in their own rights which exist independently of any entities which can be located at them. This view of spacetime can be called "absolutist" or "the container view". In BFO, the class "span:ProcessualContext" ("processual_context") allows for a so-called relational view of spacetime, that is to say, a view according to which spatiotemporality is a matter of relative location between entities and not a matter of being tied to spacetime. In BFO, the bridge between these two views is secured through the fact that instances of "span:ProcessualContext" ("processual_context") are too spatiotemporal entities.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:SpaceTimeRegion" ("space_time_region") that has spatial and temporal dimensions and every spatial and temporal point of which is not connected with every other spatial and temporal point of which.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the space and time occupied by the individual games of the World Cup, the space and time occupied by the individual liaisons in a romantic affair

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:SpaceTimeRegion" ("space_time_region") that has temporal and spatial dimensions such that all points within the spatiotemporal region are mediately or immediately connected to all other points within the same "span:SpaceTimeRegion" ("space_time_region").

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the spatial and temporal location of an individual organism's life, the spatial and temporal location of the development of a fetus

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:ConnectedSpaceTimeRegion" ("connected_space_time_region") that endures for more than a single moment of time.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the space time region occupied by a process or by a fiat processual part

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:ConnectedSpaceTimeRegion" ("connected_space_time_region") at a specific moment.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the space time region occupied by a single instantaneous temporal slice (part) of a process

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") that exists in time by occurring or happening, has temporal parts and always involves and depends on some entity.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the life of an organism, the process of meiosis, the course of a disease, the flight of a bird

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") consisting of a characteristic spatial shape inhering in some arrangement of other "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") entities. "span:ProcessualContext" ("processual_context") entities are characteristically entities at or in which other "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") entities can be located or occur.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: The processual context for a given manipulation occurring as part of an experiment is made of processual entities which occur in parallel, are not necessarily all parts of the experiment themselves and may involve "snap:Continuant" ("continuant") entities which are in the spatial vicinity of the participants in the experiment.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: An instance of a "span:ProcessualContext" ("processual_context") is a mixture of "span:ProcessualEntity" ("processual_entity") which stand as surrounding environments for other "span:ProcessualEntity" ("processual_entity") entities. The class "span:ProcessualContext" ("processual_context") is the analogous among "span:Occurrent" ("occurrent") entities to the class "snap:Site" ("site") among "snap:Continuant" ("continuant") entities.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:ProcessualEntity" ("processual_entity") that is the fiat or bona fide instantaneous temporal process boundary.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: birth, death, the forming of a synapse, the onset of REM sleep, the detaching of a finger in an industrial accident, the final separation of two cells at the end of cell-division, the incision at the beginning of a surgery

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:ProcessualEntity" ("processual_entity") that is a meriological sum of "span:Process" ("process") entities and possesses non-connected boundaries.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the beating of the hearts of each of seven individuals in the room, the playing of each of the members of an orchestra, a process of digestion and a process of thinking taken together

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:ProcessualEntity" ("processual_entity") that is a maximally connected spatio-temporal whole and has bona fide beginnings and endings corresponding to real discontinuities.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the life of an organism, the process of sleeping, the process of cell-division

attribute.name: j.0:externallySourcedDefinition
attribute.value: * Complex mental function having four distinct phases: (1) memorizing or learning, (2) retention, (3) recall, and (4) recognition. Clinically, it is usually subdivided into immediate, recent, and remote memory. (MSH) * Memory; the power of retaining and recalling past experience, something that is remembered. (NCI) * The activities involved in the mental information processing system that receives (registers), modifies, stores, and retrieves informational stimuli. The main stages involved in the formation and retrieval of memory are encoding (processing of received information by acquisition), storage (building a permanent record of received information as a result of consolidation) and retrieval (calling back the stored information and use it in a suitable way to execute a given task). [http://cancerweb.ncl.ac.uk/, http://www.onelook.com/, ISBN:0582227089] (GO) * mental function underlying learning; one model specifies 4 phases: acquisition, retention, recall, and recognition. (CSP)

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "span:ProcessualEntity" ("processual_entity") that is part of a process but that does not have bona fide beginnings and endings corresponding to real discontinuities.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: chewing during a meal, the middle part of a rainstorm, the worst part of a heart-attack, the most interesting part of Van Gogh's life

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "bfo:Entity" ("entity") that exists in full at any time in which it exists at all, persists through time while maintaining its identity and has no temporal parts.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: a heart, a person, the color of a tomato, the mass of a cloud, a symphony orchestra, the disposition of blood to coagulate, the lawn and atmosphere in front of our building

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "snap:IndependentContinuant" ("independent_continuant") that is neither bearer of "snap:Quality" ("quality") entities nor inheres in any other entities.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the sum total of all space in the universe, parts of the sum total of all space in the universe

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: An instance of "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") is a part of space. All parts of space are "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") entities and only "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") entities are parts of space. Space is the entire extent of the spatial universe, a designated individual, which is thus itself a "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region").

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: All instances of "snap:Continuant" ("continuant") are spatial entities, that is, they enter in the relation of (spatial) location with "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") entities. As a particular case, the exact spatial location of a "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") is this region itself.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: Space and "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") entities are entities in their own rights which exist independently of any entities which can be located at them. This view of space is sometimes called "absolutist" or "the container view". In BFO, the class "snap:Site" ("site") allows for a so-called relational view of space, that is to say, a view according to which spatiality is a matter of relative location between entities and not a matter of being tied to space. The bridge between these two views is secured through the fact that while instances of "snap:Site" ("site") are not "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") entities, they are nevertheless spatial entities.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the surface of a cube-shaped part of space, the surface of a sphere-shaped part of space, the surface of a rectilinear planar figure-shaped part of space

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: a cube-shaped part of space, a sphere-shaped part of space

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the part of space that is a line stretching from one end of absolute space to the other, an edge of a cube-shaped part of space

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "snap:Continuant" ("continuant") that is a bearer of "snap:Quality" ("quality") and "snap:RealizableEntity" ("realizable_entity") entities, in which other entities inhere and which itself cannot inhere in anything.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: an organism, a heart, a leg, a person, a symphony orchestra, a chair, the bottom right portion of a human torso, the lawn and atmosphere in front of our building

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "snap:IndependentContinuant" ("independent_continuant") consisting of a characteristic spatial shape in relation to some arrangement of other "snap:Continuant" ("continuant") entities and of the medium which is enclosed in whole or in part by this characteristic spatial shape. "snap:Site" ("site") entities are entities that can be occupied by other "snap:Continuant" ("continuant") entities.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: a particular room in a particular hospital, Maria's nostril or her intestines for a variety of bacteria.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: An instance of "snap:Site" ("Site") is a mixture of "snap:IndependentContinuant" ("independent_continuant") entities which act as surrounding environments for other "snap:IndependentContinuant" ("independent_continuant") entities, most importantly for instances of "snap:Object" ("object"). A "snap:Site" ("site") is typically made of "snap:Object" ("object") or "snap:FiatObjectPart" ("fiat_object_part") entities and a surrounding medium in which is found a "snap:Object" ("object") occupying the "snap:Site" ("site"). "snap:IndependentContinuant" ("independent_continuant") entities may be associated with others (which, then, are sites) through a relation of "occupation". That relation is connected to, but distinct from, the relation of spatial location. "snap:Site" ("site") entities are not to be confused with "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") entities. In BFO, "snap:Site" ("site") allows for a so-called relational view of space which is different from the view corresponding to the class "snap:SpatialRegion" ("spatial_region") (see the comment on this class).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Region of the spine within several hundred nanometers of the post synaptic specialization characterized by the presence of coated pits. It is believed that this zone may be specialized for endocytosis. These coated pits are never observed in membrane associated with the post synaptic specialization (Blanpied and Ehlers, 2004).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Site defined with respect to the Node of Ranvier, e.g., node, paranode, juxtaparanode

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Region of nodal complex adjacent to the nodal region

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Site located at the gaps in the myelin sheaths of myelinated axons. Axon diameter is generally decreased in the nodal region, compared to the internode. Ranvier's nodes allow saltatory conduction, that is, jumping of impulses from node to node, which is faster and more energetically favorable than continuous conduction (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Region of nodal complex adjacent to the paranode

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Part of nodal complex located underneath the compact myelin in between nodes of Ranvier

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Tubular structures of relatively uniform size that connect mitochondrial cristae to the inner mitchondrial membrane (Perkins and Ellisman, 2003).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Sites of close apposition of the inner and outer mitochondrial membrane (Perkins and Frey, 2000).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Site of contact between the inner and outer mitochondrial membrane found in neuronal mitochondria; may play a role in maintaining the structural integrity of the inner and outer boundary membranes (Perkins and Ellisman, 2005).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The site of cell-cell contact containing a morphologically identified junctional complex joining the two cells.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: The Cell_Cell_Contact_Zone and the Intercellular_Junction are not the same. The junction only refers to the bridging complex and not the larger region where the junction resides. The intercellular_Junction is part of a larger cell-cell contact zone. The cell-cell contact zone may also contain additional junctions and cellular machinery related to the function of the junction.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A belt-like region of very close contact between the plasma membranes of adjacent cells so that the intercellular space is completely occluded. They occur in epithelia and brain endothelia (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Adherent, symmetrical junction characterized by widened extracellular space and filamentous material (Peters, Palay and Webster, 1991).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A small version of the zonula adharens type junction, characterized by a symmetrical adherent point between two cells.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A specialized presynaptic plasma membrane region where synaptic vesicles dock and fuse (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: An intercellular junction found in invertebrate epithelia that is characterised by a ladder like appearance in electron micrographs. Thought to provide structural strength and to provide a barrier to diffusion of solutes through the intercellular space. Occur widely in transporting epithelia and are controversially considered analogous to tight junctions (zonula occludens) Biology-online.org

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Any specialized areas of the plasma membranes of adjacent cells where the membranes are 2-4 nm apart and penetrated by a connexon (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: That part of a multicellular organism outside the cells proper, usually taken to be outside the plasma membranes, and occupied by fluid (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The narrow gap that separates the presynaptic and postsynaptic membranes, into which a neurotransmitter is released (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Anatomical space occurring within a cell, usually formed by intracellular membranes.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The volume enclosed by the membrane or protein that forms a vesicle (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the smooth endoplasmic reticulum (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: From Reactime: Regions within compact myelin in which the cytoplasmic faces of the enveloping myelin sheath are not tightly juxtaposed, and include cytoplasm from the cell responsible for making the myelin. Schmidt-Lanterman clefts occur in the compact myelin internode, while lateral loops are analogous structures found in the paranodal region adjacent to the nodes of Ranvier.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the rough endoplasmic reticulum (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Spaces defined by the inner and outer mitochondrial membranes

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Interior portion of mitochondrion bounded by the inner mitochondrial membrane and cristae membranes and containing the mitochondrial matrix. Does not include the crista or crista lumen.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the mitochondrial envelope. (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: I'm having difficulty deciding whether this is a regional part of a mitochondrion or whether it is a site; today it is a regional part.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The space bounded by the cristae membrane

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The space between the inner and outer nuclear membranes

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The volume enclosed by the membranes of an endosome (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Extended zone of intimate apposition between two cells containing one or more types of intercellular junctions, e.g., the intercalated disk of muscle

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: We still don't know if the synapse, in the sense that it is typically used, belongs here or whether large, multicontact synapses like the neuromuscular junction and the calycl synapse of Held, belong here and not simple synapses

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Contact between endothelial cell and pericyte consisting of membrane invaginations extending from either cell type, which contain tight-, gap-, and adherence junctions (Armulik et al., Circ Res 97: 512, 2005).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Contact site between adjacent cells in cardiac muscle fibers. When observing tissue through a microscope, this is an identifying feature of cardiac muscle.It holds the myofibrils together and permits easy transfer of excitation (depolarization).

attribute.value: third ventricle of the mammalian brain.

attribute.name: j.2:example
attribute.value: sulcal invaginations of the mammalian brain.

attribute.name: j.0:externallySourcedDefinition

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "snap:IndependentContinuant" ("independent_continuant") that is a lower dimensional part of a spatial entity, normally a closed two-dimensional surface. Boundaries are those privileged parts of "snap:Object" ("object") entities that exist at exactly the point where the "snap:Object" ("object") is separated off from the rest of the existing entities in the world.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: the surface of the skin, the surface of the earth, the surface of the interior of the stomach, the outer surface of a cell or cell wall

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Comment: Boundaries are theoretically difficult entities to account for, however the intuitive notion of a physical boundary as a surface of some sort (whether inside or outside of a thing) will generally serve as a good guide for the use of this universal.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "snap:IndependentContinuant" ("independent_continuant") that is a mereological sum of separate "snap:Object" ("object") entities and possesses non-connected boundaries.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: a heap of stones, a group of commuters on the subway, a collection of random bacteria, a flock of geese, the patients in a hospital

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A morphological or functional domain formed by parts of two or more cells, e.g., neuropil, dendritic bundles.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Supracellular structure formed by the descending axon collaterals of several cerebellar basket cells that wrap around the Purkinje cell initial segment. Although the axons contain many vesicles and form terminal endings, most do not synapse directly on the Purkinje cell initial segment but rather end blindly.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A dense intricate feltwork of interwoven fine glial processes, fibrils, synaptic terminals, axons, and dendrites interspersed among the nerve cells in the gray matter of the central nervous system (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Large synaptic bouton found in areas like olfactory bulb, cerebellar cortex and thalamus, that contacts many post-synaptic targets.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The junction between a nerve fiber of one neuron and another neuron or muscle fiber or glial cell; the site of interneuronal communication. As the nerve fiber approaches the synapse it enlarges into a specialized structure, the presynaptic nerve ending, which contains mitochondria and synaptic vesicles. At the tip of the nerve ending is the presynaptic membrane; facing it, and separated from it by a minute cleft (the synaptic cleft) is a specialized area of membrane on the receiving cell, known as the postsynaptic membrane. In response to the arrival of nerve impulses, the presynaptic nerve ending secretes molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Existence of both chemical and electrotonic synapses at the same interface (Peters, Palay and Webster, 1991).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Synaptic contact characterized by both electrical and chemical synaptic junctions.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Electrotonic synapses are gap junctions that allow the passage of ions directly from cell to cell. Ultrastructurally, it can be recognized as a 7 layered structure with 4 dense lines, two from each of the plasma membranes, alternating with 3 lighter lines. Electrotonic synapses are generally symmetric and display little or no dense material associated with the cytoplasmic face of the plasma membrane (Peters, Palay and Webster, 1991).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Type of synapse characterized by an electron-dense ribbon, lamella (bar) or spherical body in the presynaptic process cytoplasm (Sjostrand, 1953; Ladman, 1958; Gray and Pease, 1971). It usually sits in or just above an evaginated ridge of the terminal membrane..." - Dowling (1987)

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a post-synaptic potential responsible of the muscle contraction (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: An intercellular junction recognized in electron micrographs as a 7 layered structure with 4 dense lines, two from each of the plasma membranes, alternating with 3 lighter lines. The plaque is composed of multiple intercellular gap junction channels.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Need to determine what is the proper relationships between an electrotonic synapse and a gap junction

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: An insoluble mass of misfolded proteins.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Irregularly shaped clumps of denatured or misfolded proteins observed in some neurons after a period of ischemia that stain heavily with osmium in electon microscopic preparations.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Insoluble fibrous protein aggregation sharing specific structural traits.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Abnormal structures located in distal dendrites. Filamentous bundles made up of straight and paried helical filaments which contain ubiquitin and tau.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Junctional complex consisting of two connexons that come together to form a communicating pore between two cells

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: This is a placeholder. This refers to a protein configuration, but we think it belongs elsewhere. A fibril is actually a minute fiber or filament. Filament could refer to protein filament. A long chain of proteins, such as those found in hair, muscle, or in flagella

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Two threads of tau protein that are wound around each other.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Delicate fibrils of collagen in connective tissue. It is composed of molecules of tropocollagen aggregated in linear array.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A fibril composed of amyloid protein.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Insoluble fibrils that form in pathological conditions characterized by Lewy bodies, such as Parkinson's disease, dementia with Lewy bodies, and multiple system atrophy. Alpha-synuclein is the primary structural component.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A configuration of somatic spines found on ciliary ganglion neurons in the embryonic and adult brain consisting of patches of closely spaced spines lying flat against the soma. (Shoop et al., 2000).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: The entire complement of dendrites for a neuron, consisting of each primary dendrite and all its branches.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A multiribosomal structure representing a linear array of ribosomes held together by messenger RNA. They represent the active complexes in cellular protein synthesis and are able to incorporate amino acids into polypeptides both in vivo and in vitro. (From Rieger et al., Glossary of Genetics: Classical and Molecular, 5th ed) (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Square arrays of closely spaced intramembrane particles, 4-6 nm in size seen in astrocyte processes, now known to contain aquaporins.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Stacks of rough endoplasmic reticulum that stain intensely with basophilic dyes.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A configuration of ER found in Purkinje cells in the cerebellum and in axons in the lateral vestibular nucleus, consisting of a number of parallel and interconnecting tubules whose outer surfaces are covered by particles or ringlike structures (Peters, Palay and Webster, 1991).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Assembly of 6 connexins into a hemichannel that forms one half of a gap junction. In some cells, the hemichannel is active as a conduit between the cytoplasm and the extracellular space.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Definition: A "snap:IndependentContinuant" ("independent_continuant") that is spatially extended, maximally self-connected and self-contained (the parts of a substance are not separated from each other by spatial gaps) and possesses an internal unity. The identity of substantial "snap:Object" ("object") entities is independent of that of other entities and can be maintained through time.

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Examples: an organism, a heart, a chair, a lung, an apple

attribute.name: rdfs:comment
attribute.value: Want to organize this more carefully in the next version of the SAo

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Membrane proteins which facilitate the passage of water. They are members of the family of membrane channel proteins which includes the lens major intrinsic protein and bacterial glycerol transporters (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A highly conserved small regulatory protein used in to label old, damaged, or misfolded proteins for destruction in a proteasome. Ubiquitous in eukaryotes.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Integral membrane proteins that transport molecules or ions into or out of the cell or compartment.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Transports adenine nucleotides (AMP, ADP, and ATP) across membranes (Gene Ontology).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Diverse group of viral, prokaryotic, and eukaryotic proteins which interact with specific sites on DNA or its associated proteins to initiate or inhibit transcription; not all are DNA binding proteins per se, although that is a BT (CSP).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Synuclein is a small, soluble protein primarily expressed in neural tissue and in certain tumors. The synuclein family includes three known proteins: alpha-Synuclein, beta-Synuclein and gamma-Synuclein.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A synuclein protein found primarily in the peripheral nervous system (in primary sensory neurons, sympathetic neurons, and motor neurons) and retina. It is also detected in the brain, ovarian tumors, breast tumors, and in the olfactory epithelium. It is the least conserved of the synuclein proteins.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A synuclein protein found primarily in brain tissue and seen mainly in presynaptic terminals. It is predominantly expressed in the neocortex, hippocampus, striatum, thalamus, and cerebellum. It is not found in lewy bodies, but it is associated with hippocampal pathology in Parkinson's disease and dimentia with Lewy bodies.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Predominantly a presynaptic neuronal protein of unknown function, but can also be found in flial cells. Expressed particularly in the neocortex, hippocampus, striatum, thalamus, and cerebellum. It is normally an unstructured protein yet it can aggregate to form incoluble fibrils in pathological conditions characterized by Lewy bodies. It is the primary structural component of Lewy body fibrils and an alpha-synuclein fragment, known as the non-ABeta component (NAC) is found in amyloid plaques.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: An alpha-Synuclein fragment found in amyloid plaques in Alzheimer's disease.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A 919-amino-acid protein that interacts with alpha-synuclein.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A synaptic protein expressed predominantly in the outer nuclear retinal layer. It is expressed, at a lower level, in the brain.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A family of synaptic vesicle-associated proteins involved in the short-term regulation of neurotransmitter release. Synapsin I (Protein I), the predominant member of this family, links synaptic vesicles to actin filaments in the presynaptic nerve terminal. These interactions are modulated by the reversible phosphorylation of synapsin I through various signal transduction pathways. The protein is also a substrate for cAMP- and calcium-calmodulin-dependent protein kinases. It is believed that these functional properties are also shared by synapsin II (Protein III) (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A large family of monomeric GTP-binding proteins that are involved in regulation of actin organization, gene expression and cell cycle progression. EC 3.6.1.- (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A cytoplasmic neuronal protein containing two ring-finger domains and a ubiquitin-like dmain at its amino terminus.

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Sodium dependent transport protein, located on presynaptic terminals, involved in the uptake of dopamine; site at which cocaine exerts rewarding/ reinforcing effects (CSP).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: An enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of L-tyrosine, tetrahydrobiopterin, and oxygen to 3,4-dihydroxy-L-phenylalanine, dihydrobiopterin, and water. EC 1.14.16.2 (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A synthetic enzyme that catalyzes the formation of acetylcholine from acetyl-CoA and choline. EC 2.3.1.6 (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: An enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of acetylcholine to choline and acetate. In the CNS, this enzyme plays a role in the function of peripheral neuromuscular junctions. EC 3.1.1.7. (MSH)

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A group of 7 proteins produced from a single gene by alternate splicing found in central and peripheral nervous system myelin. The major basic protein (MBP) has long been of interest because it is the antigen, that, when injected into an animal, elicits a cellular immune response that produces the CNS autoimmune disease called experimental allergic encephalomyelitis (encephalomyelitis, allergic). In the peripheral nervous system, myelin basic protein 18.5 kD is often referred to as the P1 protein. (From Siegel et al., Basic Neurochemistry, 5th ed, p130, 133) (MSH)

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Protein based machines that are involved in or cause movement such as the rotary devices (flagellar motor and the F1 ATPase) or the devices whose movement is directed along cytoskeletal filaments (myosin, kinesin and dynein motor families) (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A family of high molecular weight GTP phosphohydrolases that play a direct role in vesicle transport. They associate with microtubule bundles (microtubules) and are believed to produce mechanical force via a process linked to GTP hydrolysis (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A class of cellular receptors that have an intrinsic protein-tyrosine kinase activity (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Cell surface receptors that bind signalling molecules released by neurons and convert these signals into intracellular changes influencing the behavior of cells. Neurotransmitter is used here in its most general sense, including not only messengers that act to regulate ion channels, but also those which act on second messenger systems and those which may act at a distance from their release sites. Included are receptors for neuromodulators, neuroregulators, neuromediators, and neurohumors, whether or not located at synapses (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Cell-surface proteins that bind glutamate and trigger changes which influence the behavior of cells. Glutamate receptors include ionotropic receptors (AMPA, kainate, and N-methyl-D-aspartate receptors), which directly control ion channels, and metabotropic receptors which act through second messenger systems. Glutamate receptors are the most common mediators of fast excitatory synaptic transmission in the central nervous system. They have also been implicated in the mechanisms of memory and of many diseases (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: A class of ionotropic glutamate receptors characterized by affinity for N-methyl-D-aspartate. NMDA receptors have an allosteric binding site for glycine which must be occupied for the channel to open efficiently and a site within the channel itself to which magnesium ions bind in a voltage-dependent manner. The positive voltage dependence of channel conductance and the high permeability of the conducting channel to calcium ions (as well as to monovalent cations) are important in excitotoxicity and neuronal plasticity (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Cell surface proteins that bind glutamate and directly gate ion channels in cell membranes. AMPA receptors were originally discriminated from other glutamate receptors by their affinity for the agonist AMPA (alpha-amino-3-hydroxy-5-methyl-4-isoxazolepropionic acid). They are probably the most common mediators of fast excitatory synaptic transmission in the central nervous system. Several subtypes have been cloned, and for some types the traditional distinction from kainate receptors may not apply (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Cell surface proteins that bind acetylcholine with high affinity and trigger intracellular changes influencing the behavior of cells. Cholinergic receptors are divided into two major classes, muscarinic and nicotinic, based originally on their affinity for nicotine and muscarine. Each group is further subdivided based on pharmacology, location, mode of action, and/or molecular biology (MSH).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: Classic ligand-gated ion channel receptor type, where binding of ligand (acetylcholine) to transmembrane protein oligomer causes channel to open, permitting ion (sodium and potassium) flux and depolarization (CSP).

attribute.name: sao:definition
attribute.value: G-protein coupled surface receptor that mediates acetylcholine action on smooth and cardiac muscle and in CNS; may be linked to a potassium channel (membrane polarization) or second messenger systems (CSP).

attribute.value: Additional agonists from V Ralevic and G Burnstock, Pharm. Rev., v50:n3, p413 (BB).
